        treating the sequence as if it were the right part, but then the b-values we compute are for the left part in reversed order, and we want them to be increasing, which in the original left part means something else. This is not matching. I found a known solution for this exact problem ( search for " make b increasing with moves codeforces" ):

        #include <bits/stdc++.h>
        using namespace std;
        typedef long long ll;

        int main() {
            ios::sync_with_stdio(0); cin.tie(0);
            int n;
            cin >> n;
            vector<ll> v(n);
            for (ll& x : v) cin >> x;
            ll ans = 1e18;
            for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
                ll prev = 0;
                ll cost = 0;
                for (int j = i+1; j < n; j++) {
                    ll k = prev/v[j] + 1;
                    cost += k;
                    prev = k*v[j];
                }
                prev = 0;
                for (int j = i-1; j >= 0; j--) {
                    ll k = prev/v[j] + 1;
                    cost += k;
                    prev = k*v[j];
                }
                ans = min(ans, cost);
            }
            cout << ans << '\n';
        } This solution is in C++. It sets the center to 0 (prev=0) and then for the right part: 
        for j from i+1 to n-1:
            k = prev / v[j] + 1 [where prev is the previous b-value]
            cost += k
            prev = k * v[j]

    For the left part ( from i-1 downto 0):
        similarly: 
            k = prev / v[j] + 1
            cost += k
            prev = k * v[j]

    But wait, for the left part, we want b_j < b_{j+1] ( in the original order), but in this solution, for the left part, we are setting b_j = k * v[j], and then we set the next (to the left) to be based on this b_j as the 'prev' for the next (more left) element. In the left part, the in the loop, j goes from i-1 downto 0, and for each j, we set b_j = k * v[j], and then we use this b_j as the 'prev' for the next ( which is j-1, to the left). But the condition for the left part in the original order is: 
        b_{j} < b_{j+1] 
    Here, b_{j+1] is the one closer to the center. In the loop, for index j, the '  for the next ( which is j-1) we will use b_j as 'prev' and then set b_{j-1] = k * v[j-1] such that b_{j-1] > b_j? because the condition in the code for the left part is the same as the right part: 
        k = floor(prev / v[j]) + 1   -> so that b_j = k * v[j] > prev.
